This column is not the primary key but provides a unique value to ensure distinct identification across distributed systems and databases. It is typically used for synchronization purposes or when a unique identifier is required for integrations across different databases or systems. The values in this column are generated to be unique across space and time, ensuring no duplicates occur. Such GUIDs are crucial when requiring a non-intelligent unique value that is not related to the business logic of the data.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.ProductDescription table stores the date and time when a particular product description record was last altered. This column is of the datetime data type, indicating it captures both date and time components. It is essential for tracking changes and maintaining an accurate history of record modifications in the database. This information is useful for identifying the most recent updates and synchronizing records that have changed over time. When generating a SQL query, ModifiedDate can be used for filtering or ordering data based on recency of changes.

tables.name: SalesLT.Product
tables.description: The SalesLT.Product table is a comprehensive dataset that contains information about various products available in the database. Each product is uniquely identified by a ProductID, serving as the primary key, while other characteristics such as name, product number, color, size, weight, and pricing details provide a detailed description of each product's specifications. The table also includes category and model identifiers, as well as sales and lifecycle dates, helping to manage product availability and history. Additionally, it includes image data for product thumbnails, along with unique global identifiers for each record. This table is pivotal for queries related to product identification, categorization, pricing analysis, and sales operations.

columns.name: ProductID
columns.definition: The ProductID column in the SalesLT.Product table is a primary key column containing unique integer values used to identify each product in the database. As it is a primary key, each ProductID is distinct, ensuring that no two rows within the table share the same identifier. This column is essential for establishing relationships with other tables in the database that might reference products by their unique IDs. Being an integer type, ProductID supports efficient indexing and searching operations, making it a critical component for querying and managing product-related data within the database. When generating SQL queries involving this column, one can filter or join data based on ProductID, ensuring precise and unambiguous selections of product records.

columns.name: Name
columns.definition: The "Name" column in the "SalesLT.Product" table is of type "nvarchar", which means it is used to store variable-length string data. This column contains the names of products, providing a textual identifier or description that is typically human-readable and known to customers and business users. The values in this column are intended to represent the unique names of different products sold, ranging from general categories such as "All-Purpose Bike Stand" to specific items like "AWC Logo Cap". This column is not a primary key, which suggests the product names may not be unique across the table, and could potentially contain similar or duplicate values. When filtering or querying records related to product names, this column can be useful for identifying specific products based on their given descriptors.

columns.name: ProductNumber
columns.definition: The ProductNumber column in the SalesLT.Product table contains unique alphanumeric identifiers for each product. This column is essential for tracking and differentiating products across various operations, such as inventory management and sales processing. The data type for this column is nvarchar, indicating it can store both numeric and alphabetic characters, allowing for a wide variety of formatting styles. Product numbers often have specific patterns, which can be useful for querying particular groups of products, such as those starting with a certain prefix or containing specific segments. This column is not a primary key but works alongside the ProductID to help ensure product uniqueness and integrity.

columns.name: Color
columns.definition: The "Color" column in the "SalesLT.Product" table represents the color attribute associated with each product. This column contains text values that specify the colors in which products are available, such as 'Black', 'Blue', 'Grey', and various other color names or combinations like 'Silver/Black'. The data type of this column is "nvarchar", indicating that it can store a wide range of color names in different languages or formats. It is not the primary key, meaning that multiple products can share the same color value, and it may contain duplicate entries across different products. This column is useful for filtering and categorizing products based on their color in queries.

columns.name: StandardCost
columns.definition: The "StandardCost" column in the SalesLT.Product table represents the production cost incurred for manufacturing each product. It is of type money, indicating it stores monetary values and is crucial for calculating profit margins when compared to the "ListPrice" column. The data in this column is typically used to analyze cost management, pricing strategies, and profitability of products. Ensuring accuracy in this column allows for effective budgeting and financial planning in sales operations.

columns.name: ListPrice
columns.definition: The "ListPrice" column in the "SalesLT.Product" table contains monetary values representing the listed selling price of each product. This column is crucial for pricing analysis and comparisons, as it provides the base price at which products are sold to customers before any discounts or offers are applied. The data type is "money," indicating the values are expressed in a currency format, which is important for transactions and financial calculations. Typically, this column is used alongside other columns like "StandardCost" to evaluate profit margins and pricing strategies. Filtering based on "ListPrice" can help identify products within a specific price range for targeted promotions or inventory assessments.

columns.name: Size
columns.definition: The "Size" column in the "SalesLT.Product" table stores the size information of a product, represented as a string in the "nvarchar" data type. This column likely indicates measurements pertinent to the product, such as dimensions for clothing or components in the product line. Sizes are typically given as a series of numbers, reflecting standardized size values like "38", "40", "42", etc. This column is not a primary key and could be used for filtering or categorizing products based on their size in queries. It's important to interpret the size values consistently within the context of specific products to ensure accurate data handling and reporting.

columns.name: Weight
columns.definition: The Weight column in the SalesLT.Product table contains decimal values that represent the weight of the products. The data type is decimal, allowing for precise representation of weight, which is crucial for products sold by weight or where shipping weight matters. The values in this column can include null, indicating that certain products do not have a specified weight, perhaps because it is not applicable or available. Analyzing this column can help filter products based on their weight, which is useful for inventory management, shipping calculations, and product comparisons.

columns.name: ProductCategoryID
columns.definition: The ProductCategoryID column in the SalesLT.Product table is an integer field that represents a unique identifier for the category to which a product belongs. This column plays a key role in categorizing products within the database, linking each product to a specific category. It allows for efficient retrieval and organization of products based on their categories, which is essential for queries that filter or group products by category. Understanding the ProductCategoryID is crucial for accurately handling and querying product data, as it establishes the relationship between products and their broader categories. This column is typically used in conjunction with other tables that define category details for comprehensive data analysis and reporting.

columns.name: ProductModelID
columns.definition: The ProductModelID column in the SalesLT.Product table is an integer column that identifies the model of a product. Each product is associated with a specific ProductModelID, which acts as a reference to distinguish different product models within the database. This column can be used to join with other tables that contain detailed information about each product model, allowing for comprehensive analysis and queries about product specifics. Because it is not a primary key, multiple products can share the same ProductModelID, indicating that they belong to the same model. When querying this column, filters can be applied to select particular product models of interest.

columns.name: SellStartDate
columns.definition: The SellStartDate column in the SalesLT.Product table records the date and time when a product becomes available for sale. This column is of the datetime data type, indicating that it includes both date and time components. It is used to track the initial availability of each product, helping in sales analysis, inventory planning, and lifecycle management. When generating a SQL query, this column is crucial for filtering products based on their availability start date, allowing queries to select products that were available within specific time frames.

columns.name: SellEndDate
columns.definition: The SellEndDate column in the SalesLT.Product table captures the date when the product was last available for sale. The column is of datetime data type and may contain null values, indicating that some products might still be available for sale, with no defined end date. The presence of this column suggests it is used to manage product lifecycle, determining whether a product should be considered for current inventory or promotions. Users querying this column should consider null checks to identify products that are still being sold. This information is vital for inventory and sales analysis to determine which products are no longer available for purchase.

columns.name: DiscontinuedDate
columns.definition: The DiscontinuedDate column in the SalesLT.Product table holds datetime values indicating when a product was officially discontinued or removed from availability. This column helps in determining the lifecycle of a product, specifically the end of its availability period. If the value is null, it suggests that the product is still available and has not been discontinued. This column is essential for querying to identify products that are no longer in circulation and to potentially calculate the duration that products were active in the market. The date format follows the standard datetime format used in SQL databases.

columns.name: ThumbNailPhoto
columns.definition: The ThumbNailPhoto column in the SalesLT.Product table is a varbinary data type used to store the binary data of a product's thumbnail image. This column contains the raw image data for the corresponding product's thumbnail, allowing the application to display a small, preview image to users. Although the specific values are not provided, this field is integral to the visual representation of products within the database. When generating queries involving this column, ensure that the binary data handling is appropriately managed for display or export purposes. It is typically used together with ThumbnailPhotoFileName to provide context for the image data.

columns.name: ThumbnailPhotoFileName
columns.definition: The ThumbnailPhotoFileName column in the SalesLT.Product table contains the file names of thumbnail images associated with various products. The data type is nvarchar, which indicates the filenames are stored as Unicode character strings. These filenames typically correspond to small image files representing the product visually, often including descriptors of the product and size in the name. This column is not a primary key, meaning it may contain duplicate file names or null values for products without associated thumbnails. When generating a SQL query involving this column, consider filtering based on the presence of specific file names or patterns within the filenames if necessary.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The rowguid column in the SalesLT.Product table is a uniqueidentifier data type, which is used to store globally unique identifiers (GUIDs). This column contains a unique value for each row in the table, ensuring that each product entry can be distinctly identified across distributed systems or databases. The rowguid is commonly used in replication scenarios and for applications requiring a unique reference for products beyond the usual primary key. This column is not a primary key but serves as an auxiliary way to maintain unique identification for operation and data consistency purposes. When querying or filtering data, this column can be used to retrieve specific product information based on its unique GUID value.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The "ModifiedDate" column in the "SalesLT.Product" table is a datetime field that records the last date and time when the product record was modified. This column helps in tracking changes to the product information over time, making it essential for auditing and version control. The values in this column are typically used to filter and identify records that have been updated within a specific timeframe or to ensure that the most recent data is being used in reports or operations. It can be used in queries to determine the recency of the data and check for updates compared to a certain date and time.

tables.name: SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription
tables.description: The SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table serves as a linking entity that associates product models with their respective descriptions and cultural contexts. Each product model can have multiple descriptions characterized by different cultural codes. The table ensures uniqueness through a combination of ProductModelID, ProductDescriptionID, and Culture as primary keys. It supports the retrieval and management of product descriptions across different languages or locales, providing essential data for globalized applications and systems. Additionally, a unique identifier and modification date are included for tracking and data integrity purposes.

columns.name: ProductModelID
columns.definition: The column ProductModelID in the SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table is an integer that serves as a primary key. It uniquely identifies each product model within this table, linking a product model to its corresponding descriptions and cultural information. Each product model can be associated with multiple product descriptions, but the ProductModelID ensures that the model itself is distinct. This column is essential for joining or filtering operations within queries that involve product models and their related descriptions. It is used to distinguish different product models in the database effectively.

columns.name: ProductModelID
columns.definition: The "ProductModelID" column in the "SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription" table is a unique identifier for each product model. It is an integer data type and serves as a primary key, indicating that it is used to uniquely identify each row within the table. The values in this column correspond to different product models, and each one is associated with one or more product descriptions. When querying this column, it is important to note its role as a primary key, which ensures that each "ProductModelID" value is distinct and corresponds directly to a specific product model record.

columns.name: ProductDescriptionID
columns.definition: The ProductDescriptionID column in the SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table is an integer type and serves as a primary key. This column uniquely identifies each product description related to a product model. The values contained in this column represent various descriptions of products that are associated with different product models. Since it is a primary key, each value in this column is distinct, enabling the identification of unique product descriptions. The column plays a crucial role in linking product models to their particular descriptions within the database schema.

columns.name: ProductDescriptionID
columns.definition: The ProductDescriptionID column is an integer field in the SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table, serving as a primary key alongside Culture. It uniquely identifies each product description associated with a product model, ensuring the combination of ProductDescriptionID and Culture provides a distinct linkage within the dataset. This column is crucial for joining tables where detailed product descriptions are needed in different languages or cultural contexts. When generating queries, this field can be used to filter or reference specific product descriptions across various product models.

columns.name: Culture
columns.definition: The "Culture" column in the "SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription" table contains data represented as fixed-width character strings (nchar). This column is used to specify the culture or locale associated with a particular product model and description combination. It likely employs standardized cultural codes, such as language identifiers (e.g., "en" for English, "fr" for French), sometimes with regional or script variations (e.g., "zh-cht" for Traditional Chinese). As a primary key, the "Culture" values ensure unique combinations with other primary key columns in the table, facilitating the retrieval and differentiation of culture-specific product descriptions. Data integrity and proper querying would rely on understanding the specific cultural codes in use within this column.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table is of type uniqueidentifier, which serves as a globally unique identifier for each record. This column ensures each entry has a distinct and unique value, making it useful for identifying and tracking records across distributed systems or merging datasets from different sources. Although it is not a primary key in this table, its uniqueness helps maintain data integrity and prevents duplication. It typically contains a lengthy string of alphanumeric characters formatted as a GUID (Globally Unique Identifier). This column is commonly used for internal data processes and is particularly helpful when records must maintain uniqueness outside the constraints of numeric identifiers.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.ProductModelProductDescription table stores the date and time when a record was last updated. It is of the datetime data type, indicating it includes both the date and time components. This column helps in tracking changes to records for auditing purposes or understanding when data was updated. It can be used for filtering records based on their modification timestamps to retrieve records modified within a certain timeframe.

tables.name: SalesLT.ProductCategory
tables.description: The SalesLT.ProductCategory table stores information about different product categories within a business's inventory system. Each product category is uniquely identified by a primary key, allowing for efficient data retrieval and management. This table supports hierarchical categorization of products, enabling the organization of categories into a parent-child relationship structure. It also includes attributes like descriptive names for the categories, unique identifiers for technical purposes, and timestamps to track modifications. The table is essential for organizing and analyzing products, facilitating queries that require category-based filtering, grouping, or hierarchical analysis.

columns.name: ProductCategoryID
columns.definition: The ProductCategoryID column is an integer type column that serves as the primary key for the SalesLT.ProductCategory table. Each value in this column uniquely identifies a product category within the dataset. It is used to establish relationships between product categories and other related tables that may reference product categories by their unique ID. Being a primary key, the values in this column are distinct and should be used for joining with foreign key columns in other tables for analyzing product category data. This column helps in maintaining the integrity and efficiency of categorizing and retrieving product data.

columns.name: ParentProductCategoryID
columns.definition: The ParentProductCategoryID column in the SalesLT.ProductCategory table is an integer column that represents the hierarchical relationship among product categories. It is used to identify the immediate parent category of a given product category, with the value of ParentProductCategoryID being the ProductCategoryID of the parent. If the column is null, it indicates that the product category is a top-level category with no parent. This column is essential for constructing queries that require traversing or analyzing the product category hierarchy. It supports understanding the relationships between categories, particularly when performing aggregation or categorization tasks.

columns.name: Name
columns.definition: The "Name" column in the SalesLT.ProductCategory table contains descriptive labels for product categories. It is an nvarchar type, indicating it stores Unicode strings, which suggests that it can accommodate a wide range of alphanumeric characters, including letters from various alphabets. The purpose of this column is to provide meaningful, human-readable descriptions for each product category, such as "Accessories" or "Bikes." It is not a primary key but is essential for identifying and organizing products into logical groupings, which can be used in SQL queries for filtering, grouping, or joining operations based on product category names.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.ProductCategory table stores a unique identifier for each record in the form of a GUID (Globally Unique Identifier). It is of the data type "uniqueidentifier" and ensures each row in the table has a unique value that can be used for replication or other purposes requiring a unique key. Unlike primary keys which may have business logic, the rowguid serves primarily as a technical identifier with no inherent meaning related to the data. While it is not a primary key in this table, it is often used in scenarios requiring globally unique values, such as distributed databases. This column is particularly useful when performing operations involving synchronization or integration with other systems.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.ProductCategory table is of the datetime data type and records the last date and time a record was altered. This column is used to track changes or updates made to each product category entry, allowing users to understand the recency of data modifications. The information can be useful for auditing purposes, ensuring data integrity, and synchronizing data changes with other systems. When formulating SQL queries, this column may be used to filter records based on when they were last updated, for instance, by retrieving records modified after a certain date.

tables.name: dbo.BuildVersion
tables.description: The dbo.BuildVersion table appears to manage records related to different versions of a database system. Each record is uniquely identified by a SystemInformationID, which serves as its primary key. The table includes key information such as the version of the database, along with timestamps to indicate when each version was recorded and when the record was last updated. This structure supports tracking and auditing the development and update history of the database system, allowing for detailed insight into version changes over time.

columns.name: SystemInformationID
columns.definition: The column SystemInformationID in the dbo.BuildVersion table is a primary key of type tinyint, which uniquely identifies each record in the table. This column serves as the identifier for different system information entries, suggesting that each entry corresponds to a distinct build version or system update. As a numeric identifier, it is crucial for maintaining record integrity and supporting relational database operations. In constructing queries, filtering by specific SystemInformationID values will allow the retrieval of precise build version details.

columns.name: Database Version
columns.definition: The "Database Version" column in the dbo.BuildVersion table stores version information of the database as a string, which is likely formatted as an nvarchar data type. This column is not a primary key, suggesting that multiple entries with different system information IDs may reference different database versions over time. The data within this column indicates the specific version of the database currently or previously in use, which can be useful in tracking changes or updates to the database schema or data. Typically, this column would be used in queries to determine the version of the database for maintenance or compatibility purposes.

columns.name: VersionDate
columns.definition: The VersionDate column in the dbo.BuildVersion table is of the datetime data type and stores the specific date and time when a particular version entry was recorded or became effective. It captures the chronological point for when changes or updates to the database version occurred. This column is essential for tracking the history and timeline of the database versions, which can be useful for auditing purposes or understanding the deployment schedule of system updates. When querying this column, consider using date functions and filters to pinpoint specific version changes over time.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the dbo.BuildVersion table is a datetime field that records the date and time when a particular record was last updated. This column is crucial for tracking changes and maintaining a history of updates to the build version records in the database. It allows users to perform queries that can filter or sort records based on their modification timestamps. This is particularly useful for data analysis and auditing purposes, ensuring that users can identify the most recent updates or changes made to the data.

tables.name: dbo.ErrorLog
tables.description: The "dbo.ErrorLog" table is designed to store detailed information about errors that occur within a system or application. Each entry in the table corresponds to an individual error event and includes data such as the time of occurrence, associated user, error code and severity, and specifics about the location in the code like the procedure and line number where the error occurred. It serves as a critical resource for troubleshooting and diagnosing system issues by offering comprehensive details on each error, which can be used to identify patterns, urgency, and specific areas in need of attention. This table is essential for maintaining system reliability and ensuring effective error management by providing both structured identifiers and descriptive messages about each error.

columns.name: ErrorLogID
columns.definition: The ErrorLogID column in the dbo.ErrorLog table serves as the primary key, uniquely identifying each record within the error log. It is an integer data type, meaning it holds whole numbers, and it ensures that each entry in the table has a distinct identifier, which is crucial for data integrity and retrieval purposes. This column is typically used to reference specific error log entries when querying the database, making it essential for any operations that require accessing or filtering individual log records. It acts as a critical component in identifying and sorting the error records efficiently within the database management system.

columns.name: ErrorTime
columns.definition: The ErrorTime column in the dbo.ErrorLog table captures the exact date and time when an error occurred within the system. It is a datetime data type, which means it records both the date and the specific time down to seconds or milliseconds, providing a precise timestamp of the error event. This information is crucial for tracking and diagnosing issues, as it allows users to identify when errors happen and correlate them with other events in the system. When querying this column, you may want to filter error records within a specific time range to analyze error frequency and patterns over time.

columns.name: UserName
columns.definition: The UserName column in the dbo.ErrorLog table stores the name of the user associated with a specific error event in the system. This column is of the nvarchar type, indicating it contains string data of variable length. It plays a crucial role in identifying which user was involved at the time the error occurred, providing a way to trace user activity in relation to system errors. When querying this column, you will typically filter or select based on specific user names to analyze their error log patterns or investigate issues related to their activities.

columns.name: ErrorNumber
columns.definition: The ErrorNumber column in the dbo.ErrorLog table stores integer values that represent specific error codes associated with events or issues recorded in the error log. These error codes are used to identify distinct types of errors encountered within the system or application. Each ErrorNumber corresponds to a specific error condition, which can be useful for troubleshooting and categorizing the issues. When generating a SQL query involving the ErrorNumber column, it is essential to filter or analyze these codes to understand the frequency and types of errors that occur.

columns.name: ErrorSeverity
columns.definition: The ErrorSeverity column in the dbo.ErrorLog table is an integer type that categorizes the seriousness of errors recorded in the system. This column likely uses a pre-defined range of numeric values to indicate different levels of severity, such as informational, warning, or critical errors. Understanding the value of ErrorSeverity is crucial for filtering error logs by the importance or urgency of the errors. Depending on the value of this column, different responses or priorities may be associated with handling the errors logged in the table. This column is essential for maintaining and examining error tracking and management in applications or systems.

columns.name: ErrorState
columns.definition: The "ErrorState" column in the "dbo.ErrorLog" table is of type integer and is used to record the state of an error when it occurs within the application or database. It provides additional context or detail about an error in conjunction with the "ErrorNumber" and "ErrorSeverity" columns, helping to differentiate between different instances or conditions of similar errors. Being an integer, it allows for distinct numerical values which represent specific states that can be filtered or queried to identify particular issues or patterns in the error logs. This column is crucial for troubleshooting and understanding the specific circumstances under which an error is generated.

columns.name: ErrorProcedure
columns.definition: The ErrorProcedure column in the dbo.ErrorLog table records the name of the stored procedure where an error occurred within the database system. This column contains textual information in the form of a variable-length string, allowing for details about which specific procedure was running at the time the error was detected. Understanding the entries in the ErrorProcedure column is crucial for diagnosing and troubleshooting issues related to specific database processes. The presence of a stored procedure name in this column can help developers and database administrators identify and address problems efficiently by focusing on the correct section of code.

columns.name: ErrorLine
columns.definition: The ErrorLine column in the dbo.ErrorLog table is an integer type column that records the specific line number in the code or a script where an error occurred. This information is crucial for debugging purposes, allowing developers to pinpoint the exact location of the problem within the source code. Typically, this column is used in conjunction with other columns like ErrorNumber, ErrorSeverity, and ErrorProcedure to provide a comprehensive view of an error event in the system. The ErrorLine value helps in efficiently identifying and addressing the root cause of errors by revealing their source in the codebase. This column does not contain null values as it must reference a valid line number where the error was detected.

columns.name: ErrorMessage
columns.definition: The ErrorMessage column in the dbo.ErrorLog table is used to store descriptive text detailing the specifics of an error that occurs within a system or application. This column is of type nvarchar, indicating it can store variable-length string data, which allows for capturing detailed error descriptions that aid in debugging and troubleshooting. The ErrorMessage provides a human-readable explanation of the error, which is crucial for identifying the nature and cause of the issue, making it useful when querying logs to understand and resolve errors. When generating a SQL query, filtering by specific keywords or phrases in the ErrorMessage column can help in isolating certain types of errors for analysis or reporting.

tables.name: SalesLT.Address
tables.description: The SalesLT.Address table stores information about various physical addresses, which are used predominantly in a database context for sales and distribution processes. Each address is uniquely identified by an AddressID, serving as the primary key. The table provides detailed address components including primary and optional secondary address lines, city, state or province, country or region, and postal code, representing the full spectrum of an address. Additionally, it contains a rowguid for global uniqueness across systems and a ModifiedDate to track changes. This table is essential for managing, querying, and filtering address-related information in business operations.

columns.name: AddressID
columns.definition: The AddressID column in the SalesLT.Address table serves as the primary key, uniquely identifying each record in the table. It is of integer data type, suggesting it is likely auto-incremented to ensure uniqueness for each entry. This column is essential for indexing and is commonly used in joins to relate address data to other entities or tables within a database. Given its role as a primary key, AddressID ensures that no two records can share the same identifier, maintaining data integrity and facilitating efficient data retrieval operations. This column is crucial for filtering and referencing specific address records in SQL queries.

columns.name: AddressLine1
columns.definition: The AddressLine1 column in the SalesLT.Address table contains the primary street address associated with a given address record. This column is of type nvarchar, suggesting that it can store variable-length Unicode string characters. The data typically includes street numbers and street names, and it may also include apartment or suite numbers prefixed by a '#'. This column is essential for uniquely identifying the street location part of an address, which, together with other address components such as city, state, and postal code, forms the complete address. It is not a primary key, so there may be multiple instances of the same street address in different contexts within the table.

columns.name: AddressLine2
columns.definition: The AddressLine2 column in the SalesLT.Address table is a text field of type nvarchar that stores additional information about an address, typically supplementary details not included in AddressLine1. This may include details such as floor numbers, room numbers, P.O. Box information, or specific locations within a larger address, such as a building or complex. It serves to provide more precise location information for mailing purposes or for identifying specific delivery points within an address. It is often used in conjunction with other address fields like AddressLine1, City, StateProvince, and PostalCode to form a complete address.

columns.name: City
columns.definition: The "City" column in the SalesLT.Address table contains the names of cities associated with each address entry. As an nvarchar type, it stores city names as variable-length Unicode character strings, allowing for a diverse range of city names from different countries and regions. The data within this column is not unique and can have multiple entries with the same city name, reflecting different addresses within that city. This column is crucial for filtering and querying addresses based on their city, which can be combined with other columns like "StateProvince" and "CountryRegion" for more precise location-based searches. The values can range from small towns to large metropolitan areas worldwide.

columns.name: StateProvince
columns.definition: The StateProvince column in the SalesLT.Address table contains character strings representing the state or province associated with a particular address. This column stores geographical subdivisions such as "Alberta" or "California" and is used to specify the state or province component of the address. It works in conjunction with other columns like City, CountryRegion, and PostalCode to form a complete address. The data type is nvarchar, allowing for a variable length of text entries, which includes letters and potentially other characters to accommodate the wide range of possible state or province names. This column is essential for filtering and grouping addresses based on their respective state or province in SQL queries.

columns.name: CountryRegion
columns.definition: The CountryRegion column in the SalesLT.Address table contains string values representing the name of the country or region associated with a specific address entry. This column helps in categorizing and filtering addresses by geographical location, which can be useful for regional analysis or operations like grouping sales data or shipping logistics. Typically, it includes distinct country names such as "Canada", "United States", and "United Kingdom", reflecting the addresses' national jurisdiction. When generating a SQL query, this column can be used to filter addresses based on the country or region criteria as needed. The data type nvarchar indicates it accommodates various potential country or region names, considering both textual complexity and diversity.

columns.name: PostalCode
columns.definition: The PostalCode column in the SalesLT.Address table stores the postal codes for the corresponding addresses. The data type for this column is nvarchar, which indicates that postal codes can include numbers and possibly characters to accommodate a variety of international formats. This column typically represents geographic regions or zones within a country, as defined by local postal services. In a SQL query, this column can be used to filter results or join with other tables that have address-related information. It is useful for tasks such as demographic analysis or shipping logistics and could be a key parameter when querying location-specific information.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.Address table is a uniqueidentifier that serves as a globally unique identifier for each row within the table. It ensures that each address entry is distinct and can be reliably referenced or linked with other systems or tables that use GUIDs for identification. This column is not part of the primary key but provides a unique identification for data synchronization, replication, or entity relationships across databases. Its values are unique and randomly generated, which means it doesn't naturally order or group data but is instead used for ensuring uniqueness. This column is vital for tasks that require unambiguous identification of each row, such as data merging and distributed database management.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.Address table stores datetime values that indicate when a specific address record was last updated. The data type for this column is datetime, which includes both date and time, although in practice the time component may not always be specified or relevant. This column is useful for tracking changes to address data over time and can be used to filter records based on when they were last modified. Utilizing the ModifiedDate in queries could help identify recent updates or generate reports based on the timeframe of changes.

tables.name: SalesLT.CustomerAddress
tables.description: The SalesLT.CustomerAddress table stores information regarding the association between customers and their addresses. It is designed to manage multiple addresses for each customer, detailing distinct address types such as "Main Office" or "Shipping". The table serves as a bridge between customer records and address entries, allowing efficient data retrieval and operations relating to customer locations. Key identifiers like CustomerID and AddressID ensure each customer and address have unique entries, while other columns provide additional details such as address role and change history. This setup is crucial for operations involving customer address management, linking, and auditing changes over time.

columns.name: CustomerID
columns.definition: The CustomerID column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table is an integer data type serving as a primary key that uniquely identifies each customer in the database. It is a non-nullable field, ensuring that every row in the table is associated with a specific customer. The presence of the CustomerID in multiple records within the same table may indicate that a single customer can have multiple addresses associated with them. This column is crucial for querying customer-related information and can be used to join with other tables to retrieve detailed customer data. Queries involving CustomerID can be used to filter data by specific customer records or analyze customer address relationships.

columns.name: CustomerID
columns.definition: The CustomerID column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table is an integer data type and serves as a unique identifier for each customer in the database. It is a primary key in this table, ensuring that each record is uniquely associated with a single customer. This column is crucial for linking multiple addresses or orders to a particular customer, facilitating customer-specific operations and data retrieval. Filtering and querying this column will enable operations that depend on retrieving or associating data specific to individual customers.

columns.name: AddressID
columns.definition: The AddressID column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table is an integer type field that serves as a unique identifier for addresses associated with customers. As a primary key, it ensures that each address entry in the table is distinct and can be individually accessed or referenced. This column is crucial for linking addresses to customer records, differentiating between various types of addresses such as main office or shipping locations. AddressID plays a key role in joining operations between the CustomerAddress table and other tables where address information is relevant. It is not nullable, meaning each address record must have a valid AddressID for the data integrity within the database.

columns.name: AddressID
columns.definition: The AddressID column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table serves as a unique identifier for each address associated with a customer. It is of integer type and functions as a primary key in this context, ensuring that each address entry is distinct and can be referenced independently. This column is crucial for identifying specific addresses when querying or joining tables that involve customer address information. AddressID values are used to link customer records to their respective address details, providing a way to manage and retrieve customer location data efficiently.

columns.name: AddressType
columns.definition: The AddressType column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table indicates the type of address associated with a customer. This column contains string values that describe the specific role or usage of an address, such as "Main Office" or "Shipping". It helps to categorize addresses based on their intended function for the customer, which may be necessary for operations like deliveries, billing, or customer correspondence. The data type for this column is nvarchar, allowing it to store various textual descriptions that specify the usage purpose of each address entry. Understanding the AddressType is crucial for filtering or sorting addresses based on their role in a customer's profile.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table contains uniqueidentifier values, which are globally unique identifiers (GUIDs). These GUIDs serve as unique keys to distinguish each row distinctly within the table, aiding in ensuring data integrity and identity even beyond the scope of the database. The values in the rowguid column are not typically intended for user interaction or business processes but are essential for system-level operations, such as data replication and integration. When querying this column, it is important to use the GUID values correctly to maintain the accuracy and reliability of data operations involving this table.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.CustomerAddress table is a datetime type column that records the date and time when the customer address information was last updated. This column is crucial for tracking changes and maintaining historical accuracy of the address data. It allows users to filter records based on the modification date to retrieve the most recent updates or changes within a specific timeframe. This information is particularly useful for maintaining data consistency and for auditing purposes to understand data modifications over time.

tables.name: SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail
tables.description: The SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table functions as a detailed record of individual sales transactions within a sales database. It records distinct sales order details such as the product ordered, quantity, pricing including any discounts, and the total amount for each line item in an order. The table is essential for tracking the specifics of each sales order, providing a breakdown of items sold, their associated costs, and the financial aspects of transactions, including pricing and discounts. This table is critical for detailed analysis of sales data, inventory management, and financial reporting, often working in conjunction with other tables to provide a comprehensive overview of sales performance and customer interactions.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is an integer and serves as the primary key. It uniquely identifies each sales order within the table, tracking the order details associated with customer transactions. As the primary key, each SalesOrderID is distinct, ensuring accurate association between a sales order and its respective details like product and quantity. This column is critical when joining with other tables, such as a sales header table, to compile complete information about specific sales transactions or to perform analyses on sales data.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is an integer that serves as a unique identifier for each sales order. This column is a primary key, meaning it uniquely identifies each row within the table. SalesOrderID is used to link sales order details to the main sales order, typically serving as a foreign key in related tables. It is critical for querying and filtering sales data, as it allows for the association of order details with specific sales transactions. When generating SQL queries, this column should be used to accurately retrieve and organize sales order information.

columns.name: SalesOrderDetailID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderDetailID column is an integer type and serves as a primary key in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table. It uniquely identifies each record in the table, marking each entry as a distinct sales order detail. This column does not contain duplicate values and is crucial for indexing and retrieving specific sales order details efficiently within the database. When generating SQL queries, filtering based on specific SalesOrderDetailID values can be useful for accessing unique sales order entries or for joining with other tables that might reference this identifier.

columns.name: OrderQty
columns.definition: The "OrderQty" column in the "SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail" table represents the quantity of a specific product ordered in a sales transaction. This column holds integer values limited by the "smallint" data type, indicating the quantity of items in an order. It is a non-primary key column used to calculate the total line cost in conjunction with other columns such as "UnitPrice" and "UnitPriceDiscount". The values in this column are crucial for determining the volume of items involved in the sales detail, which can be used for reporting sales activity, inventory management, and financial analysis.

columns.name: ProductID
columns.definition: The ProductID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is an integer field that serves as a foreign key linking each sales order detail entry to a specific product. This column helps identify which product was ordered for each line item in a sales order by referencing the unique identifier assigned to each product in the related product table. It is essential for joining the SalesOrderDetail table with other tables that contain detailed product information such as product name, category, and description. Values in this column are critical for filtering and retrieving sales-related data based on specific products, facilitating inventory tracking and sales analysis tasks.

columns.name: UnitPrice
columns.definition: The "UnitPrice" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the price per unit of a product at the time a sales order was placed. This column is of the "money" data type, indicating it holds monetary values which are essential for calculating the total cost of items ordered, especially when combined with quantities and potential discounts. The values in this column play a significant role in analyzing sales data, determining revenue, and understanding pricing strategies. When creating queries involving the UnitPrice column, it may be useful to consider this information for detailed sales performance analysis, price trend evaluations, and to ensure accurate financial reports.

columns.name: UnitPriceDiscount
columns.definition: The UnitPriceDiscount column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the discount applied to the unit price of a product in a sales order. This column is of type money, indicating that it holds a monetary value, likely as a decimal reflecting the discount amount. These values represent the discount offered per unit of the product, potentially as a percentage of the original UnitPrice but expressed in monetary terms. The values in this column are used to calculate the discounted total price of a sales order line item, and it is crucial for determining the final price after discounts have been applied. This column can be filtered or queried to analyze sales promotions or to calculate total savings applied in sales transactions.

columns.name: LineTotal
columns.definition: The LineTotal column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the total cost of a line item in a sales order. This value is computed as the product of the OrderQty (quantity ordered), UnitPrice (individual price per unit), and any applicable UnitPriceDiscount (discount applied to the unit price). The data type is numeric, allowing for precise calculations involving monetary values. This column is essential for reporting on sales revenue and understanding the monetary impact of each product sold in the context of an order.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table is a uniqueidentifier data type, which means it stores globally unique identifiers (GUIDs) for each record in the table. These GUIDs are automatically generated and serve as a unique identifier for each row, ensuring that every entry is distinct across the table and potentially across databases. Despite not functioning as a primary key in this table, the column provides a unique reference point that can be used in applications requiring synchronization or merging data from various sources. It is important when generating queries to recognize that the values in the "rowguid" column are distinct hexadecimal strings that are unique to each record.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderDetail table represents the date and time when a particular sales order detail record was last updated. It is of the datetime data type, capturing both the date and timestamp of the modification. This column is crucial for tracking changes and ensuring data is current within the database. It can be used to filter records to identify changes made within a specific time frame or to synchronize data updates across systems.

tables.name: SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader
tables.description: The SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is a central component for managing and tracking sales order information in a sales database. It contains a wide range of details about each sales order, such as order dates, shipping and billing addresses, customer identification, and financial data including subtotals, taxes, and total amounts due. The table also tracks metadata about the order, such as revision numbers, status, and online order flags. It serves as a hub for linking various aspects of sales orders with customers, addresses, and other related entities, vital for effective sales operations and reporting. The table's structure supports both operational and analytical needs, providing comprehensive order management and detailed insights into sales activities.

columns.name: SalesOrderID
columns.definition: The SalesOrderID column is an integer that uniquely identifies each sales order in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table, serving as the primary key for the table. This column is crucial for distinguishing each order and is used to link sales order details with other related tables. The values in this column are sequentially generated integers that ensure no two sales orders share the same identifier, facilitating efficient retrieval and management of sales order records. When querying this column, you should use specific SalesOrderID values to filter or join with other related tables to achieve the desired results.

columns.name: RevisionNumber
columns.definition: The "RevisionNumber" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is of type tinyint and typically contains integers representing the number of times a sales order has been revised. Each increment in this column indicates a revision made to the order, which may involve changes to order details, pricing, or other modifications. This column helps track the versioning of sales orders over time and ensures that any modifications are recorded. The presence and increment of values in this column can be used to filter or identify the most up-to-date version of a sales order when constructing SQL queries.

columns.name: OrderDate
columns.definition: The OrderDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the date when a sales order was placed. This column is of the datetime data type, indicating it stores both the date and time information, although time may not be displayed in typical usage. It is crucial for tracking when transactions occur and can be used to filter sales order records based on specific time ranges. Since it is not a primary key, it may contain duplicate values, reflecting multiple orders made on the same date. This column is essential for temporal analysis, reporting trends over time, and managing sales operations effectively.

columns.name: DueDate
columns.definition: The DueDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the date by which an order is expected to be completed or delivered. It is a datetime type column, indicating that it contains precise date and time information. This column is crucial for managing the timeline of sales orders as it assists in scheduling and ensuring customer satisfaction by meeting expected deadlines. In queries involving the DueDate column, you may want to filter results based on specific time frames or overdue orders to enhance order management and logistical planning.

columns.name: ShipDate
columns.definition: The "ShipDate" column in the "SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader" table is a datetime field that records the actual date on which a sales order was shipped to the customer. This column helps track the fulfillment timeline of each order, differentiating between the order date and the date the order was dispatched. It is useful for analyzing shipping efficiency, calculating delivery times, and managing customer expectations. The values in this column should reflect only orders that have been shipped, which may be further supplemented by checking the order status for shipments not yet dispatched.

columns.name: Status
columns.definition: The "Status" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is a numerical indicator represented by a tinyint data type that denotes the state of a sales order. This column is used to track the progress or completion of the order process. Each number corresponds to a specific order state or stage within the sales process, such as pending, complete, or cancelled. It is crucial for operational reporting and workflow management, as it helps in filtering or querying orders based on their status. Understanding the specific meaning of each status value is essential for correctly interpreting the sales process progression.

columns.name: OnlineOrderFlag
columns.definition: The OnlineOrderFlag column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is a bit data type used to indicate whether a sales order was placed online. A value of 1 (or true) signifies that the order was placed through an online platform, while a value of 0 (or false) denotes a non-online order, possibly placed through other traditional methods like in-store or via phone. This column is essential for filtering and analyzing sales data based on the sales channel, allowing businesses to segment their data and performance metrics based on the online sales process specifically. When querying this table, the OnlineOrderFlag can be utilized to extract insights into online versus offline sales proportions and trends.

columns.name: SalesOrderNumber
columns.definition: The SalesOrderNumber column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains the unique alphanumeric identifiers assigned to sales orders. These identifiers typically start with the prefix "SO" followed by a numeric sequence that corresponds to the SalesOrderID column value. As a non-primary key, it helps in uniquely identifying and tracking sales orders in a more readable format than a numeric ID alone. This column can be used in queries to filter or sort records based on specific sales order numbers.

columns.name: PurchaseOrderNumber
columns.definition: The PurchaseOrderNumber column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains alphanumeric values representing unique purchase order numbers associated with sales orders. Each value in this column is structured in a format starting with 'PO' followed by a series of digits. This column is not a primary key, but it serves as an identifier for tracking and managing purchase orders related to sales transactions. When querying this column, it is essential to ensure that the values are used accurately to match with specific purchase orders for data retrieval or reporting purposes.

columns.name: AccountNumber
columns.definition: The AccountNumber column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains unique alphanumeric identifiers assigned to each sales account. It is of the nvarchar data type, indicating that it is a variable-length string composed of letters and numbers. This column is essential for distinguishing accounts and linking sales orders to specific customers or businesses. Account numbers are structured in a consistent format, typically with hyphens separating segments, which may denote different components such as a customer segment, region, or specific account details. This column does not serve as a primary key, but it is crucial for account-level analysis and relationship mapping in sales data queries.

columns.name: CustomerID
columns.definition: The CustomerID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is an integer that uniquely identifies a customer associated with each sales order record. This column serves as a foreign key linking to a customer entity, allowing you to retrieve customer-related information for each particular sales order. Given the sample data, each CustomerID is distinct to a customer's transactions in the order history. The column is important for filtering or joining queries that involve customer-specific data or analyzing sales patterns by customer. It is not a primary key in this table, which indicates its role in establishing relationships with other tables in the database.

columns.name: ShipToAddressID
columns.definition: The ShipToAddressID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is an integer that serves as a foreign key to uniquely identify the specific address where the order is to be shipped. Each order in the table is associated with a ShipToAddressID, pointing to an address record that details the destination for delivery. This column is crucial for linking sales orders to their respective shipping addresses, enabling accurate and efficient order fulfillment. It is not a primary key but plays an important role in the relational structure by linking to another table, likely one that contains address information. When generating query filters involving ShipToAddressID, you should ensure to join the appropriate address table using this column to retrieve or filter data based on the shipping address requirements.

columns.name: BillToAddressID
columns.definition: The BillToAddressID column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is an integer field that represents the unique identifier for the address where the billing information for a sales order is sent. Each sales order is associated with a billing address, and this column helps in linking the sales order to its appropriate billing details. It is important for distinguishing the billing address in situations where the billing address may differ from other addresses associated with the sales, such as the shipping address. Since it is a foreign key, BillToAddressID likely references an entry in another table containing detailed address information. When creating SQL queries that utilize this column, you may want to join this table with the related address table to retrieve full billing address details.

columns.name: ShipMethod
columns.definition: The "ShipMethod" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the method used for shipping an order. This column is of the nvarchar data type, indicating that it stores text values which describe the various shipping methods available, such as carrier names or service levels. The values in this column help determine the logistics provider or shipping option chosen for delivering the sales order to the specified address. When generating SQL queries, filtering or selecting distinct "ShipMethod" values can help analyze shipping preferences or logistics performance for sales orders. Understanding these values is crucial for supply chain and order management analysis.

columns.name: CreditCardApprovalCode
columns.definition: The CreditCardApprovalCode column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is of the varchar data type and is used to store the approval code received from the credit card authorization process for a sales order. This code is typically generated by the payment processor when a customer completes a transaction using a credit card. It acts as a unique identifier for the approved transaction and may be used for tracking and verification purposes. Although there are no sample values available, it is likely to contain alphanumeric strings representing successful credit card transaction approvals. When querying this column, it would be important to filter or select values corresponding to approved transactions.

columns.name: SubTotal
columns.definition: The SubTotal column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the monetary amount of a sales order before tax and freight charges are added. This column is of the money data type, indicating that it stores currency values with precision. It is used to calculate the total cost of the items in an order, serving as the base amount from which taxes and freight are calculated to determine the final TotalDue for the order. Understanding the SubTotal is essential for financial reporting and analysis, as it provides insight into the pre-tax and pre-shipping earnings from sales orders. When querying this column, users may filter based on specific sales order criteria to analyze revenue patterns and perform budgetary assessments.

columns.name: TaxAmt
columns.definition: The "TaxAmt" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the monetary amount of tax applied to each sales order. The data type for this column is "money," which indicates that it stores currency values, often requiring precision up to four decimal places. This column is crucial for financial calculations and assessments, as it contributes to the overall TotalDue for each sales order. When querying this column, consider any necessary calculations or aggregations involving tax, such as summing tax amounts across orders or filtering for orders with specific tax characteristics.

columns.name: Freight
columns.definition: The "Freight" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the cost associated with the shipment of a sales order. It is expressed in monetary terms, indicating the charges incurred to transport goods from the seller to the buyer. This column holds data of the "money" type, which typically includes decimal values to account for precise cost calculation. The freight cost is a part of the total financial summary of an order and contributes to the "TotalDue" amount for each transaction. This value can be used to assess shipping expenses and analyze logistics efficiency for sales orders.

columns.name: TotalDue
columns.definition: The TotalDue column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table represents the total amount owed for a sales order, combining the subtotal, tax amount, and freight charges. It is a calculated field of type 'money' and is used to provide the final amount due for each order. Values in this column are numeric and typically reflect the currency used in sales transactions. This column will often be referenced when querying for sales data to determine the total financial obligation associated with specific orders. When generating queries, it is important to consider this column for summarizing or aggregating financial data related to sales orders.

columns.name: Comment
columns.definition: The "Comment" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is designed to store textual remarks or notes relevant to a specific sales order. This column is of type "nvarchar," allowing for the storage of variable-length Unicode string data. Since the sample values are not provided, it's likely used to capture additional information that may not be structured or fit into predefined categories, such as customer instructions or internal employee notes. The presence of a comment contributes context or clarification to the sales order record but is not a mandatory field. For generating SQL queries, consider including this column when querying for insights or specific order narratives that are recorded by the sales or support teams.

columns.name: rowguid
columns.definition: The "rowguid" column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table contains uniqueidentifier datatypes, which are Globally Unique Identifiers (GUIDs) used to uniquely identify each row in the table. This column is not the primary key but serves as a unique reference to ensure the uniqueness of each record, possibly for synchronization or replication purposes. The values in this column are automatically generated using the GUID generation functionality, ensuring that each value is distinct and does not duplicate any other GUID in the column. When using this column in SQL queries, you may employ it for distinct operations or joining tables where a unique reference is required beyond traditional integer keys.

columns.name: ModifiedDate
columns.definition: The ModifiedDate column in the SalesLT.SalesOrderHeader table is of the datetime data type and records the last date and time when a sales order record was altered or updated. It is used to track changes or updates to the order details after its creation. Typically, this column is pivotal for audit purposes or for generating reports based on the most recent changes to sales orders. When querying the database, this column can be used to filter records to retrieve all transactions modified within a specific timeframe, allowing for timely analysis or operational adjustments based on recent order modifications.
